\begin{center}
{\LARGE Evaluating the Accuracy of the SIR Model in Replicating Real-World Disease Outbreaks}
\end{center}

\vspace{2cm}
\noindent Epidemic modeling (EM), uses mathematics to study the spread of infectious diseases. There are various different epidemic models used in EM, we chose to study the SIR model. The SIR model divides a population into three cohorts, Susceptible, Infected, and Recovered and models the rate of change of each cohort. We studied how accurately the SIR model could replicate the outbreak patterns of measles and COVID-19, by comparing it to observed data. We concluded that the SIR model performed best when the disease had a lower $R_0$ value, most likely due to the assumptions the SIR model makes about the population.

