\section{Limitations}

The SIR model is a very simple and idealized epidemic model. We stated that the model assumes a closed population with homogeneous mixing, which is unrealistic. This assumption is a limitation to the SIR model. This then forced us to use a smaller population size in our model, which could definitely impact the outputted results. We also assumed an I(0) value, along with a $\gamma$ value which was taken from a provided range, all of which could alter the SIR model's output. The SIR model also outputs a constant curve with no dips or fluctuations in the case values, which is unrealistic.  We are also comparing the models to observed cases where there are issues of under reported cases.

\section{Conclusion}
The SIR models for measles, did not display accurate outbreak patterns. Whereas, the COVID-19 curves did. We believe this is due to the large difference in their $R_0$ values. The assumption of the effectiveness of the model based on its basic reproduction value is reasonable with the population assumptions made. A disease with a high  basic reproduction value, means one infected individual will infect more persons than that of an infected individual with a lower value. When we assume a closed homogeneous population, we are assuming the population size is not changing and everyone in the population has equal probability of coming into contact with one another. This aligns with the SIR model for measles showing the instant spike in infected individuals. If one person can infect 18 individuals, all of whom have equal probability of coming into contact, it would likely not take long for everyone to be infected. The plots for COVID-19 showed exponential growth and a peak. On average, one individual infected 1.4 to 2.5 individuals which appeared to allow the SIR model to depict realistic outbreak patterns. These results suggest that the $R_0$ value has a large impact on the accuracy of the SIR model. Based on these results we would conclude that the SIR model can be used for diseases with a lower basic reproduction value, but is not effective for diseases with an increased value. Though it is important to be aware that the model can give a general idea of an outbreak pattern, it should certainly not be the sole model used due to its generalizations.
